<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Transforming legal aid: delivering a more credible and efficient system</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Coram Children’s Legal Centre (CCLC) (LAI 0069)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Coram Children’s Legal Centre</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Coram Children’s Legal Centre </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(CCLC) is an independent NGO working in the United Kingdom and around the world to protect and promote the rights of children, through the provision of direct legal services; the publication of free legal information online and in guides; research and poli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cy work; law reform; training; and international consultancy on child rights. Founded in 1981, CCLC has over 30 years’ experience in providing legal advice and representation to children, their parents and carers and professionals throughout the UK. The CC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">LC’s legal practice specialises in education, family and immigration law and CCLC operates several free advice phone lines including the Child Law Advice Line</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the Migrant Children’s Project Advice Line.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Migrant Children’s Project at CCLC provides s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pecialist advice and legal representation to migrant and refugee children and young people on issues such as age assessment and access to support and accommodation. As part of CCLC’s work to promote the implementation of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hildren’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rights, CCLC has underta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ken amicus curiae interventions in a number of significant cases, including in the European Court of Human Rights, the Supreme Court and the Court of Appeal, providing assistance to the court on matters of children’s rights and best interests.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In this evi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ence, we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">focus on the impact of the proposals on children and young people’s access to justice and the incompatibility of the proposals with children’s human rights standards, including domestic, regional and international standards.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">No assessment of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> impact on children</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are extremely concerned about</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the lack of a child impact assessment, or even any data or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">detailed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">analysis of the impact </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of the proposals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on children and young people and their rights. We consider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that the government must carry out </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a child impact assessment in relation to the proposals.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government claims that the impact on children has been considered. It says:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">While our analysis of equalities impacts is focussed on the protected </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">characteristics set out in the Equality Act 2010, we have, throughout, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">considered carefully the impact of our proposals on vulnerable groups, with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">particular regard to the best interests of children, as addressed in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">relevant chapters, the IAs and th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e equality statement.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this is not evident in the vari</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ous documents, including Annex F: Equality Statement and the Impact </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Assessments, particularly the Impact Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> entitled 'Cumulative Legal Aid Reforms' and those with the IA numbers MoJ194</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, MoJ195 and MoJ198. None of these documents mention the best interests of children.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The analysis of the impact of the prison law proposals on children and young people is slightly more detailed than the impact on children and young people of the other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oposals.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> However, it remains insufficient and lacks any evidence of the current effectiveness of the complaints process or advocacy services to back up the contention that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">As a result of the procedures outlined ..., in particular the provision of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">advo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">cacy services and the ability to refer cases to Local Authorities, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">statutory Monitor or PPO, we consider that adequate support is prescribed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and available to ensure that under 18 prisoners are supported and provided </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">for and can resolve claims throug</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">h alternative channels such that criminal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">legal aid for prison law is not required apart from in the circumstances set </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">out in the scope criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> the removal of criminal legal aid for prison law as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">proposed should not detrimentally impact on them.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relation to the residence test, the government states: 'We acknowledge that the test as proposed may disproportionately impact on groups with protected characteristics namely non-British nationals, women and children'.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The government's response is to emph</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">asise its modifications to the residence test as originally proposed in April 2013 and to state: 'To the extent there is a disproportionate impact ... we believe that the residence test is a proportionate means of achieving the legitimate aims'.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This is i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n our view wholly inadequate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Despite the government’s responsibilities under the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child, which provides that states parties shall respect and ensure the rights of children ‘without discrimination of any kind’ (Article 2)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Equality Statement and the Impact Assessments do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not analyse the effect that the proposals will have on different groups of children and young people, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children with disabilities, BME children, children with mental health conditions and so o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government has an obligation, under the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child, to ‘undertake all appropriate legislative, administrative, and other measures for the implementation of the rights’ contained in the Convention,</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and to ensure that, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in all actions concerning children, their best interests shall be a primary consideration. This fundamental principle applies whether the actions are taken by ‘public or private social welfare institutions, courts of law, administrative authorities or legi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">slative bodies’.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This extends to the formation of government policy and legislation, and, according to the UN Committee on the Rights of the Child, child impact assessments are key to fulfilling this obligation. The Committee stated, in its General Commen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t on ‘general measures of implementation’ that: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Ensuring that the best interests of the child are a primary consideration in all actions concerning children (art. 3(1)), and that all the provisions of the Convention are respected in legislation and polic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">y development and delivery at all levels of government demands a continuous process of child impact assessment (predicting the impact of any proposed law, policy or budgetary allocation which affects children and the enjoyment of their rights) and child </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">im</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">pact evaluation (evaluating the ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">tual impact of implementation). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">This process needs to be built into government at all levels and as early as possible in the development of policy.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#231f20; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As your Committee has stated, the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">presence [of child impact </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">assessments] in the explanatory notes to a Bill would be a sign of the Government’s genuine commitment to place the best interests of the child at the heart of policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Child impact assessments are crucial to realising the obligation to ensure that childr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">en’s best interests are a primary consideration in the development of law and policy, and to ensure that government decision-making centres on the needs and interests of children.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">hildren and young people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">’s access to justice</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In our view and based on our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> experience, the proposed residence test, the proposed restrictions to prison law, the proposals relating to legal aid for judicial review, and the proposals to remove legal aid from cases with ‘borderline’ prospects of success will have an extremely negat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ive impact on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">access to justice, including on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children and young people’s rights and access to justice.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Article 3 of the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child states that the best interests of the child must be a primary consideration in all actions co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ncerning children. This is a binding international obligation and it is translated into domestic law through section 11 of the Children Act 2004 and section 55 of the Borders, Citizenship and Immigration Act 2009 (see the leading Supreme Court judgment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ZH </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(Tanzania) v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> [2011] UKSC 4). Where Article 8 ECHR rights are engaged, these are to be interpreted in accordance with the UNCRC.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Article 12 of the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child provides:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">States Parties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> shall assure to the child who is capable of forming his or her own views the right to express those views freely in all matters affecting the child, the views of the child being given due weight in accordance with the age and maturity of the child.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">For th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">is purpose, the child shall in particular be provided the opportunity to be heard in any judicial and administrative proceedings affecting the child, either directly, or through a representative or an appropriate body, in a manner consistent with the proce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">dural rules of national law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Guidelines of the Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe on child-friendly justice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> state:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-20.7pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">3.7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Children should have the right to their own legal counsel and representation, in their own name, in proceedings where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">there is, or could be, a conflict of interest between the child and the parents or other involved parties.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-20.7pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">3.8  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Children should have access to free legal aid, under the same or more lenient conditions as adults.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In recognition of the need for specific pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tection and assistance for separated children, the Committee on the Rights of the Child </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">General Comment No. 6 on the Treatment of Unaccompanied and Separated Children Outside their Country of Origin </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(2005) states that where children are involved in adminis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">trative or judicial proceedings they should be provided with legal representation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Research has demonstrated that denying legal advice and representation to young people can have a disproportionate effect on them. The evidence demonstrates that young </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">people’s legal problems tend to be severe and have a greater impact on their lives than similar problems for older adults. Young people will fare worse when they have a legal problem due to their inherent vulnerability and lack of experience with the syste</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">m.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The residence test</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are deeply concerned about the proposed residence test.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In our view, the proposals would leave thousands of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> people – including children – vulnerable to abuse by the government and unabl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e to enforce their legal rights in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significant areas of civil law. We have particular concerns about children, young people and families' inability to access civil legal aid in public law to cha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">llenge state actions and about restricting access to civil legal aid in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">areas of community ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re and special educational needs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exceptions and modifications</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to the residence test are welcome but are extremely narrowly defined.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Babies under 12 months</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> old still have to pass the first limb of the test, namely lawful residence, thus excluding fro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">m civil legal aid any baby who cannot prove lawful residence, unless they fall into one of the exemptions.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> A baby under one who is born into an undocumented migrant family and for whom legal aid is needed in their own right, for example in relation to a ju</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dicial review of unlawful actions by a local authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (such as an unmet community care need)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, would not get it.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recognised refugees</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> no longer have to wait</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for one year from the Home Office’s decision </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to grant them status </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in order to once again become eli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gible for civil legal aid (they will have been eligi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ble as asylum-seekers), but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> they still face a potentially significant gap in time </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">during which they are ineligible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">because the 12-month period of lawful residence will begin from the date they submitted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their asylum claim.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Legal aid for any ongoing civil case will continue,</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but they face a potential gap in eligibility </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">if they need civil legal aid </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for any new case. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This means that those with the promptest Home Office decisions, including those who are gr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">anted refugee status at first instance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">without having to go to appeal, are penalised by facing the longest time gap in eligibility between when they are asylum-seekers and when they re-enter eligibility through showing 12 months</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> lawful residence.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">means that resettled refugees will have to wait for one year in order to be eligible for civil legal aid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This goes against Article 16 of the Refugee Convention 1951, which provides that ‘[a] refugee shall have free access to the courts of law on the terr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">itory of all Contracting States’ and that ‘[a]</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">refugee shall enjoy in the Contracting State in which he has his habitual residence the same treatment as a national in matters pertaining to access to the Courts, including legal assistance and exemption from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cautio judicatum solvi.’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Child protection cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have been exempted as follows:</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> all care proceedings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> civil actions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in relation to abuse that took place when the person was a child</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cases in relation to the inherent jurisdiction of the High Court</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (including wardship cases and including for example the recent case of Neon Roberts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">);</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> unlawful removal of children cases</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (includi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng both domestic and international child abduction cases and locating missing children cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> where a court</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> order is necessary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">); cases where a child is provided legal services as a party in family proceedings</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (for example specific issue orders brought by children); and clinical negligence and severely disabled infants cases</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (claims for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> damages that meet the specific</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> requirement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s of LASPO).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This leaves many other types of case that relate to safeguarding childre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n subject to the residence test. This includes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for example age dispute judicial reviews </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that determine whether someone is a child (the safeguarding consequences of which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are extremely serious including a child potentially being detained in an adult prison or immigration removal centre or housed in unsupervised accommodation with adults). This also includes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">any other judicial review of the practice of local authorities or o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ther public bodies in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relation to their duties to protect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> children. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">proposed residence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> test noticeably </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">still applies to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cases concerning section 17 of the Children Act 1989 - duties to children in need.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Trafficking victims, including children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">been granted a particularly narrow exemption from the residence test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> they will not have to pass the residence test in order to get legal aid for the immigration applic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ations, employment law cases and civil damages claims </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at were protected under LASPO.</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In relation to immigration applications, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his is solely for applications for leave to enter or remain and is only available to those for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whom there has been a positive reasonable grounds or conclusive grounds decision </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by a competent authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The exempti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on thus </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">leaves very significant gaps in the civil legal aid that trafficking </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">victims can access. They will not have access to civil legal aid in public law, leaving them unable to bring a judicial review. This is striking because the only way to challenge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a negative reasonable or conclusive grounds decision is by judicial review. They will not be able to access legal aid in community care, for example if a child or young person is unlawfully denied services by a local authority or unlawfully age disputed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Victims of domestic violence and forced marriage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are exempted from the residence test as follows: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cases involving home rights, occupation orders and non-molestation orders under Part 4 of the Family Law Act 1996 and cases arising out of a family relationsh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ip relating to an injunction following assault, battery or false imprisonment or the inherent jurisdiction of the High Court;</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">family matters for victims of domestic violence;</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cases involving orders and procedures to protect children</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (removal of the fath</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s parental responsibility;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> termination of appointment of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">guardian; residence, contact and other orders; special guardianship orders; disclosure of child’s whereabouts orders, return </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of the child orders); forced marriage protection orders under Part 4A o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f the Family Law Act 1996;</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> immigration applications for indefinite leave to remain as a person who was granted leave to remain as a partner and the relationship has broken down due to domestic violence;</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and EEA applications for a residence card as a vict</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">im of domestic violence who was a family member of a qualified person but the marriage or civil partnership broke down</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and they have retained rights of residence.</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The immigration applications contained in the exemption are very narrow: it is only where a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> victim of domestic violence can make specific applications that they access civil legal for this. In our experience, many victims of domestic violence would not fall into these exemptions in relation to their immigration applications.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Moreover, the resid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ence test remains in relation to significant areas of civil law relevant to victims of domestic violence and forced marriage, including public law, community care, civil actions and actions against the police. For example, if an undocumented migrant mother</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was the victim of domestic violence, had to leave the home and was facing destitution with her children, and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">local authorit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> failed to meet its duties to the children, she would not get legal aid for a community care or public law lawyer to challenge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">etention</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cases are exempted from the residence test as follows: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mental health and mental capacity cases;</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> habeas corpus;</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> immigration detention;</span><a name="_ftnref29"></a><a href="#_ftn29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> immigration temporary admission cases;</span><a name="_ftnref30"></a><a href="#_ftn30">[30]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and immigration residence restrictions cases.</span><a name="_ftnref31"></a><a href="#_ftn31">[31]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This means tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t applications for bail made by those held in immigration detention are covered. However, immigration detainees will not be able to access civil legal aid in many important areas. This includes civil actions for damages for unlawful detention</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, or civil cla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ims arising from mistreatment in detention or discrimination</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Very significantly, age-disputed children held in immigration detention as adults will not be able to access community care or public law legal aid to challenge an unlawful age assessment by a l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ocal authority.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Judicial review</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is exempt from the residence only for judicial reviews of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> unlawful detention</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref32"></a><a href="#_ftn32">[32]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">judicial reviews of a refusal to accept further submissions as a fresh asylum claim,</span><a name="_ftnref33"></a><a href="#_ftn33">[33]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and judicial reviews of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">certifications by the Home Office </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">under section 94 or section 96 of the Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002.</span><a name="_ftnref34"></a><a href="#_ftn34">[34]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This leaves an enormo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">us array of judicial reviews </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">subject to the residence test. To take some examples from CCLC’s practice, we will not be able to challenge unlawful age assessments where a child does not pass the residence test; we will not be able to challenge unlawful failures by local authorities to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">meet duties to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children where children do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not pass the residence test; and we will not be able to bring judicial reviews to challenge the manifest failings of the Home Office in relation to children and young people where they do not meet the residence tes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t. Whole developing areas of law around </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the rights of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">those who do not have leave in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, some of the most vulnerable people in this country, are likely to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disappear. We believe limiting access to the courts in this way has extremely significant constit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">utional implications, thr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eatens the rule of law, and undermines</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the government’s obligation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s to protect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> human rights, and particularly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> children’s rights.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In summary, the government appears to have been persuaded that some groups are vulnerable, but has on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly carved out very discrete areas in which they will still be eligible for civil legal aid, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which leaves questions about</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> their commitment to really protecting these groups and their access to justice.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The original April 2013 consultation paper stated that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the first limb of the residence test would ‘have the effect of excluding, for example, illegal visa overstayers, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">clandestine entrants and failed asylum seekers from receiving c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ivil legal aid’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref35"></a><a href="#_ftn35">[35]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Who is excluded will depend on how ‘lawfully resident’ is def</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ined in the relevant secondary legislation. We are concerned that the people likely to fall within this category are among the most marginalised in the UK, and among the most at risk of breaches of their fundamental rights. A proportion of the people falli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng within this category will not be able to speak English or will speak English as a second language. Preventing their access to justice by barring them from civil legal aid will render them unable to enforce their legal rights in administrative and legal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">proceedings, thereby directly weakening the rule of law. Where unlawful decisions are made they will be without effective remedy because they will be unable to access legal advice or representation to challenge these decisions. This will result in a vast i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nequality of arms between the state and the individual subject to its power.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This inequality is particularly marked in the case of a child. The particular capabilities and vulnerabilities of children and young people clearly create distinct obstacles to t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">heir ability to seek redress and access justice. This is true of all children, but particularly true of separated children and young people who are without their families and face complex administrative and legal proceedings alone. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As is widely recognised,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> there are significant and multiple barriers to children being able</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to recognise legal problems, seek appropriate, quality legal advice and representation, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">understand and navigate complex administrative and legal processes. Children need legal support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">if their rights and the protections the law affords them are to be realised. Any reforms to the civil legal aid system must take full account of their potential impact on children, on children’s access to justice and on a child’s opportunity to be heard in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> administrative and judicial proceedings affecting them. We are concerned that the proposed residence test risks effectively cutting children off from legal redress and goes against the rule of law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Undocumented migrant children form a particularly vulner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">able group. There are an estimated 120,000 undocumented migrant children in the UK, with over half (65,000) born in the UK to undocumented migrant parents.</span><a name="_ftnref36"></a><a href="#_ftn36">[36]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> They face significant obstacles to realising their rights and accessing essential services. We are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">concerned in particular about:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Young people in the care system who have no regular immigration status</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In our experience, these young people have often been brought to the UK at a young age on a visa which then expired. They and their social workers may n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ot even realise that they have immigration issues until later in their teenage years. Too often local authorities fail to meet their duties to these young people. If the proposals go through, they would not be able to access civil legal aid for a lawyer in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> community care or public law to challenge such instances. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ntext of the LASPO changes, the proposals take</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on even greater significance, as these young people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">already </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cannot get immigration legal aid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for their substantive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">immigration </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> further take away their ability to get legal aid for judicial review, for example if the Home Office </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">acts unlawfully</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, thus potentially increasing the burden falling on local authorities who would have to pay privately for an immigration judicial review wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ere this was necessary to meet the needs of a child or young </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">person to whom they owed duties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, the proposals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also mean that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">if a local authority refused to pay </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for private immigration legal services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">where they have a duty to do so, a child or y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oung person would not get civil legal aid for community care or public law to challenge this.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Children in undocumented migrant families</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> facing destitution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref37"></a><a href="#_ftn37">[37]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> These families have no recourse to public funds and, with their parents frequently not allowed to work, can experience exceptional poverty. Local authorities owe duties to these children if they are 'in need' under section 17 of the Children Act 1989, but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in our experience, local authorities too often unlawfully fail to assess needs or withhold or withdraw support from these children. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Removing civil legal aid from these families</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would lead to the disappearance of a whole developing area of law around these</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> children's rights. It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would in our view significantly increase</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the risks of destitution and neglect for this vulnerable group of children.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disabled children in undocumented migrant families</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Duties to children in need include duties to all disabled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children, but in our experience legal assistance is sometimes required in order to ensure disabled children, including those without regular immigration status, receive the support to which they are entitled in law.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Children with special educational needs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in undocumented migrant families</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Publicly funded </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">legal assistance in this area is now </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">subject to a telephone gateway and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCLC is one of three providers of remaining publicly funded services in this area of law. Under the proposed residence test, no undoc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">umented family with a child who has special educational needs would be able to access such services, for example if the local authority was failing to provide suitable education. This is despite the fact that the duties to children under the Education Act </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1996 are blind to immigration status. Removing civil legal aid for those unlawfully in the UK would j</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eopardise children's education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rights.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Children in undocumented migrant families with family law issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> While</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> certain Children Act 1989 provisions are ex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">empt from the residence test, there are still questions about family law. For most families unable to access legal aid in private family law since 1 April 2013, mediation is available as an alternative, and the government has been keen to promote this. Und</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ocumented families, meanwhile, will not be able to go to court and will also not be able to access mediation, raising the question of how they are expected to resolve private family disputes and what should happen to children in these circumstances.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Children in undocumented migrant families with housing law issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Legal aid for housing is highly restricted under LASPO. Furthermore, those unlawfully in the UK are ineligible for much housing assistance. Nevertheless, there are still cases where</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> familie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s, for example those facing unlawful eviction, would need housing legal aid and will be unable to access it because they fail the residence test.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Undocumented migrants </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">subject to unlawful discrimination</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Undocumented migrants will not be able to bring any</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> claims on the basis of discrimination under the proposals. They will not be able to avail themselves of the protections the law provides.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The proposals are not about tightening the law in relation to migrants’ treatment or access to services or entitleme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nts. Such access is already restricted through numerous other pieces of legislation and regulations, and may</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be restricted further through the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> forthcoming Immigration Bill. Rather, the proposals relate to people’s ability to challenge a failure to treat th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">em in the way they are entitled to be treated under UK law, where they have a right in law to challenge it. If there were no legal entitlement in respect of the treatment or services in question or there were no right to challenge it, they would in any cas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e not pass the merits test for legal aid. The proposals would take away legal aid from those with meritorious cases, denying them access to the courts and weakening the rule of law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government noted that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Respondents raised particular concerns about the lack of assessment of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">impact on children and specifically child victims of human trafficking. Many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">responses highlighted the protections afforded to children by the United </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Nations Convention on the Ri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ghts of the Child (UNCRC).</span><a name="_ftnref38"></a><a href="#_ftn38">[38]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, the government says: ‘We do not accept the view that the proposed residence test would result in contravention of our domestic and international legal obligations ... we would ensure that legal aid will continue to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">available where necessary to comply with our obligations u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nder EU or international law set</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> out in Schedule 1 to LASPO.’</span><a name="_ftnref39"></a><a href="#_ftn39">[39]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This is based on the supposed availability of except</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ional funding as a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">safeguard for those excluded from legal aid by the residence tes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We share the views of the Public Law Project</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Dr Nick Armstrong</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and others about the inadequacy of the exceptional funding system </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to act as a safeguard </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and its failures since 1 April 2013. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To our knowledge, only nine grants have been made since 1 April 2013. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Furthermore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it is inappropriate for children’s access to justice to be provided by way of an ‘exception’. In our view the residence test breaches ch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ildren’s rights and is unlawful, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the exceptional funding scheme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> fails to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> remedy this.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As well as those who are excluded from civil legal aid because they cannot meet the residence test, there will be thousands more people, including children and young people, who meet the test but are un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">able to provide evidence for this, and therefore face additional barriers in accessing the legal assistance that they need. It is already difficult enough for children, young people and their families to access the legal support they need and the impositio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n of a residence test will make it even harder.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Prison law</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are very concerned that the government is withdrawing legal aid from prison law, including for children and young people in Secure Children’s Homes, Secure Training Centres and Young Offender</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Institutions. We are concerned that the government ‘does not intend to make an exception for those under the age of 18’.</span><a name="_ftnref40"></a><a href="#_ftn40">[40]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Children and young people in prison are some of the most vulnerable children and young people in the country. They require legal sup</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">port with the matters the government proposes to remove from legal aid, including for example local authority provision of services to them upon release. In our experience, local authorities too often do not meet their duties to children and young people a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd so they require legal support to ensure that their rights are upheld. The proposals will leave children and young people in the prison system unable to challenge breaches of their rights.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is not adequate for the government to base its withdrawal on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the fact </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">all youth secure esta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">blishments are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">required to have comprehensive internal complaints systems’</span><a name="_ftnref41"></a><a href="#_ftn41">[41]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> if in practice such systems are inaccessible or ineffective in meeting children and young people’s needs. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Those with mental health problems and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">learning disabilities face additional obstacles in accessing these systems and procedures. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government recognises that ‘young people may find it more challenging to navigate the complaints process, grievance or disciplinary procedures’</span><a name="_ftnref42"></a><a href="#_ftn42">[42]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but suggests tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t advocacy services within the secure estate can address this. In our experience, these advocacy services cannot resolve the legal issues that many of these children and young people face. Good advocacy services are vitally important, but they cannot repla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ce legal support where there is a legal issue and where a public body such as a local authority is not meeting its duties to a child or young person. Having an advocate to ‘accompany a young person to meetings on request either to support the individual or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> represent their wishes’</span><a name="_ftnref43"></a><a href="#_ftn43">[43]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is not the same as having a specialist lawyer.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are concerned that young people subject to immigration control who are in prison will be even less able than they currently are to access the legal assistance that they require to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> address their immigration issues, because</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> they will not have prison lawyers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who may have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">en</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> able to pick up on the issues and make appropriate referrals. Children and young people who are unidentified victims of trafficking within the prison system will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> also be affected by the proposals and the proposals would make their identification as victims less likely.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our other concern is with the children of parents who are in prison. The ability of children to visit and have contact with their parents in priso</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n goes to the heart of the family life rights and the best interests of children. The treatment cases for which legal aid will no longer be available include mother and baby cases, where mothers are refused places on the unit and the ability to be with the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ir babies (Annex B(b) of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">original Transforming Legal Aid </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consultation paper). Prisoners’ correspondence and visits with their children are among the proposed issues for which there would be no legal aid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Judicial review</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government’s proposals for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> judicial review</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, as set out in a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> further consultation entitled ‘Judicial Review: Proposals for Further Reform’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, are broader than just covering legal aid, but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> we concentrate in this evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on the legal aid aspects and in particular the proposal relating to permission work in judicial review cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that was originally proposed in the April 2013 ‘Transforming Legal Aid’ consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We hope that the Committee will be considering the wider jud</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">icial review proposals in addition to the present inquiry.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The newly introduced possibility of providers applying to the Legal Aid Agency to receive a discretionary payment for work done on a permission application will not, in our view,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be effective in remedying the defects of the proposal. Providers will be involved in an overly burdensome process, both for themselves and the Legal Aid Agency, in making such applications with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">supporting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evidence according to the proposed criteria.</span><a name="_ftnref44"></a><a href="#_ftn44">[44]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Man</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">providers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have expressed concerns about their inability to c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arry the risk that this proposal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> place</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on providers and these are concerns that we share as a legal aid provider.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We are also concerned about any</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> perverse incentive to issue proceedings. It is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">never ideal for a child to be involved in litigation and we consider that any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reform that makes it less likely that a case will be settled at an early stage is likely to be detrimental to children, for whom the best outcomes are achieved when the public bo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dy settles at an early stage.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are concerned about the undermining of children and young people's ability to access legal assistance for judicial review if the proposals go ahead, as providers are unlikely to be found who are willing to take on the many</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cases where judicial review is the necessary course of action to challenge failures by public bodies in relation to children and young people. This check on state action is, we believe, of particular importance for children and young people, and the propo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sals threaten children and young people's ability to enforce the rights and protections the law provides them.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Borderline cases</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The proposal is intended to save approximately £1 million per year by removing legal aid from any civil case where the merits </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are assessed as borderline, of which there were approximately 100 in 2011/12 according to information provided in the Impact Assessment.</span><a name="_ftnref45"></a><a href="#_ftn45">[45]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> However, the figures are only</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> very approximate as: 'All savings figures have been rounded to the nearest £1m' and '[a]</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ll volume changes have been rounded to the nearest 100 cases'.</span><a name="_ftnref46"></a><a href="#_ftn46">[46]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The statistics provided in the Impact Assessment show that of the approximately 100 borderline cases in 2011/12, 38% were 'Other Public Law Children' cases, i.e. public law family matters tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t do not fall within the definition of Special Children Act cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. If </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such a large proportion of borderline cases involv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e public law children cases, we consider that it is inappropriate for the government not to have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">specifically considered the impact of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his proposal on children. In our view the cases that will be affected will include cases that are of significant importance for children.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are concerned about this proposal because it will impact on test cases. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ases </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">concerning children's rights </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oft</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">en </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">likely to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cases, which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">involve a signifi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cant wider public interest. I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">important that these cases receive legal aid funding to test points of law in relation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to children and it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">essential, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in order that the rights of children are upheld</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">providers are able to take on difficult and complex </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">legal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">challenges involving novel points of law</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in relation to children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Only in this way can it be ensured that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the law </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fully promotes, protects and fulfils the rights of children, and that duty-be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arers are fully cognisant of their legal obligations to children and young people.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">13</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Transforming Legal Aid: Next steps, Annex B: Response to consultation, par</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">a. 475</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Transforming Legal Aid: Next steps, Annex F: Equality Statement, page 187 and following</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Transforming Legal Aid: Next steps, Annex F: Equality Statement, para. 9.2.20</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Transforming Legal Aid: Next steps, Annex F: Equality Statement, para. 11.2.9</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Transforming Legal Aid: Next steps, Annex F: Equality Statement, para. 11.2.13</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Article 4, UN Convention on the Rights of the Child 1989</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Article 3, UN Conventio